      0DTE
   =20
 =20

Let=E2=80=99s say you own a bunch of stocks, say $1 million worth of the st=
ocks in the S&P 500 Index. You think they will go up (that=E2=80=99s why yo=
u own them), but you worry that they might go down. You can buy insurance a=
gainst that risk: You can pay someone a fee now, and she will guarantee you=
 that, in a year, your S&P 500 stocks will be worth at least $1 million. If=
 they=E2=80=99re not, she=E2=80=99ll pay you the difference. (If they=E2=80=
=99re worth more than $1 million, you keep the gains, but she keeps the fee=
.) This is a put option.
The fee for that insurance is about $50,000: You pay about 5% of the value =
of your portfolio to insure it against a drop for one year.
  [1]
=C2=A0That=E2=80=99s kind of a lot? If the S&P goes down by 20%, you=E2=80=
=99ll be happy you bought insurance, but if it goes down by 4% you won=E2=
=80=99t be: You=E2=80=99d have been better off taking that loss and not pay=
ing 5% upfront.
  [2]
 If the S&P goes=C2=A0up=C2=A0by 20%, you won=E2=80=99t mind your insurance=
 that much =E2=80=94=C2=A0you still made 15%, net of insurance costs =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but if it goes up by 5% you=E2=80=99ll be bummed; the cost of insu=
rance wiped out all of your gains.
You might want cheaper insurance. One way to get cheaper insurance is to in=
sure against only particular risks. One relatively simple way to do that=C2=
=A0would be to buy insurance only on particular=C2=A0days.
  [3]
 If the Federal Reserve has a monetary=C2=A0policy announcement scheduled o=
ne Wednesday afternoon, and you worry that the Fed might raise rates and th=
at this will be bad for your stocks, you could buy insurance on your stocks=
 for=C2=A0that day:=C2=A0If your stocks go down that day, you get paid the =
difference, but if they don=E2=80=99t, your insurance premium is wasted. Th=
at insurance is relatively cheap: Buying a day of protection costs a lot le=
ss than buying a year of protection. I mean, it costs a lot more=C2=A0per d=
ay=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0a one-day put costs more than 1/365th as much
  [4]
 as a one-year put =E2=80=94 but if you pick the right days maybe you save =
money.
Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   Lu Wang reports:

Investors are wagering on the daily gyrations of American equity benchmarks=
 by dashing in and out of trading contracts that expire within 24 hours =E2=
=80=94 known by the =E2=80=9C0DTE=E2=80=9D moniker =E2=80=94 with less upfr=
ont capital than meets the eye. The hidden fuel for the frenzy: Quirks in t=
he ecosystem of the derivatives marketplace that makes these zero-days-to-e=
xpiry options look cheap.
The best way to observe the phenomenon is in the difference between how muc=
h investors are actually spending on 0DTE and the notional value of those o=
ptions =E2=80=94 that is, how much exposure they are getting to the underly=
ing asset via the contracts.
On the latter, the notional trading volume of 0DTE for the S&P 500 currentl=
y averages a beefy $516 billion a day, according to data compiled by Cboe G=
lobal Markets. Yet the actual amount of money paid out for them, or the pre=
mium, is only $520 million.
Put another way, traders are getting $1,000 of stock exposure for every dol=
lar they spend on 0DTE. They would need to spend 10 times that to get the s=
ame equity position using derivatives with a longer lifespan, a Bloomberg a=
nalysis on Cboe=E2=80=99s data shows.
=E2=80=9CThey are the fantasy football of option trading,=E2=80=9D said Den=
nis Davitt, co-manager of the MDP Low Volatility Fund. =E2=80=9CYou spend a=
 dollar and you see if it goes your way. Then you=E2=80=99re done at the en=
d of the day.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

Getting exposure to $1,000 worth of stocks forever costs about $1,000. Gett=
ing exposure to $1,000 worth of stocks for=C2=A0one day=C2=A0costs about $1=
. What is the economic case for getting exposure to $1,000 worth of stocks =
for one day? Why would you want that? Oh, mostly gambling, but also very ta=
rgeted hedging:

On March 22, for example, when the Federal Reserve was about to announce it=
s monetary policy in the afternoon, the S&P 500 opened at about 4,002. At t=
hat time, an at-the-money put =E2=80=94 a protective contract where the str=
ike price is essentially the same as where the index is actually trading =
=E2=80=94 cost about $26 for an expiry in the same session. A similar contr=
act maturing two days later could be bought for roughly $37 =E2=80=94 or 42=
% more than the 0DTE.
=E2=80=9CThere are very meticulous use cases for 0DTE options that did not =
exist previously,=E2=80=9D said=C2=A0Jonathan Zaionz, senior derivatives an=
alyst at Cboe. =E2=80=9CSince people are taking shorter term views and/or h=
edging with 0DTE, they don=E2=80=99t need to pay as much in time premium co=
mpared to longer term strategies.=E2=80=9D

I want to read a story about a long-term buy-and-hold passive index investo=
r who (1) buys a bunch of the S&P 500, (2) never sells it and (3) has reeee=
eeally good timing doing occasional hedges with 0DTE options. I am not sure=
 that that=E2=80=99s=C2=A0much=C2=A0of what is going on here, and I=E2=80=
=99m not sure that that would exactly count as =E2=80=9Clong-term buy-and-h=
old passive index investing,=E2=80=9D but it would be cool.
Also, last week   Wang and Isabelle Lee reported:

Defiance ETFs is launching a fund on Thursday that sells ultra short-dated =
options on the Nasdaq 100 as part of its strategy. The product will be the =
first in the market to utilize so-called zero-day-to-expiration contracts, =
or 0DTE, as part of its design.
The fund will write puts =E2=80=94 bearish contracts that offer the buyer p=
rotection from index declines =E2=80=94 to generate income. By offering opt=
ions with such a short lifespan, the Defiance Nasdaq 100 Enhanced Options I=
ncome ETF (ticker QQQY) will be able to sell contracts more frequently, acc=
ording to the issuer.=C2=A0

