   =20
 =20

Bank additional tier 1 capital securities are, I think, basically a trick. =
The trick works like this:
=09AT1s kind of look like bonds =E2=80=94=C2=A0they pay regular interest, t=
hey usually get paid back after five or 10 years =E2=80=94=C2=A0so investor=
s treat them like bonds. In particular, the interest payment on a bank=E2=
=80=99s AT1s will normally be lower than the bank=E2=80=99s cost of equity =
capital, and so banks will issue AT1s because they=E2=80=99re cheaper than =
issuing equity.=09If the bank runs into trouble, the AT1s act like stock: T=
hey absorb losses so that governments, taxpayers, depositors, etc. don=E2=
=80=99t have to. The AT1s are sort of the first line of defense against ban=
k bailouts. In some ways, some AT1s are actually=C2=A0junior to=C2=A0equity=
:=C2=A0Many AT1s, by their terms, go to zero if a bank=E2=80=99s common equ=
ity capital ratio falls below 7%; at that point, the common stock is still =
worth something but the AT1s are worth nothing. This fact makes regulators =
like AT1s =E2=80=94=C2=A0they are very helpfully loss-absorbing =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and so regulators treat them as good bank capital, a good substitute =
for=C2=A0some of a bank=E2=80=99s common stock.

Investors think of AT1s as almost like bonds; regulators think of AT1s as a=
lmost like stock. And so banks can issue AT1s that, for regulatory purposes=
, are treated almost like stock, but that, economically, are not nearly as =
expensive as stock. So banks often optimize their capital structures by iss=
uing as much AT1 capital as they are allowed to. A big European bank with a=
 lot of common equity but no AT1 capital is leaving money on the table: It =
should buy back some stock and issue more AT1s to be more efficient.
A few years ago I wrote: =E2=80=9CIf the regulators think that they=E2=80=
=99re equity and the investors think that they=E2=80=99re debt, probably so=
meone is wrong!=E2=80=9D And then we have checked in a few times when the i=
nvestors have been wrong. (I should say, I tend not to write about AT1s whe=
n they just pay regular interest and then get redeemed at par at their firs=
t call date; most of the time, the investors are right that AT1s look like =
bonds.) Most notably, when Credit Suisse Group AG blew up and was acquired =
by UBS Group AG this year, some $17 billion of Credit Suisse AT1s were writ=
ten down to zero, and the holders were understandably upset. In particular,=
 they were upset that Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s common=C2=A0shareholders=C2=
=A0got paid something, while the AT1s got zeroed. If you think that AT1s ar=
e bonds, then this is an outrage: The bonds are supposed to be senior to th=
e common stock. If you think that AT1s are the first loss absorber to preve=
nt bailouts, as Swiss regulators do, then this is great. (As I argued at th=
e time, the Credit Suisse AT1s were=C2=A0designed by their terms to go to z=
ero even if the stock is worth something, so the regulators are right as a =
general matter, though the AT1 holders have some decent technical arguments=
 about the exact events that triggered their writedown.)
From UBS=E2=80=99s perspective, this was basically a sweet deal: It was abl=
e to buy Credit Suisse and get rid of $17 billion of Credit Suisse=E2=80=99=
s debt, or quasi-debt, because the Swiss regulators insisted that Credit Su=
isse=E2=80=99s AT1s vanish. On the other hand, it leaves UBS with an ineffi=
cient capital structure: That $17 billion of AT1s was cheap capital, and no=
w it is gone; zeroing it effectively increased UBS=E2=80=99s common equity =
capital, but common equity is not what it wants.=C2=A0Efficiency demands th=
at UBS issue more AT1s to buy back some stock. Because,=C2=A0still, AT1 is =
cheaper than common equity,=C2=A0even for UBS, even after the recent high-p=
rofile Credit Suisse experience of zeroing the AT1s while the common equity=
 got paid.=C2=A0
Well, probably the AT1 is cheaper. Yesterday the Financial Times checked in=
 with UBS on its AT1 program:

UBS is under pressure to replace up to $17bn of Credit Suisse AT1 bonds in =
the coming years to improve the efficiency of the enlarged bank=E2=80=99s c=
apital structure and free up funds for shareholder returns and potential ac=
quisitions.
But some investors remain wary after bondholders lost billions of dollars d=
uring the rescue of Credit Suisse when an emergency law brought in by the S=
wiss government allowed the country=E2=80=99s financial regulator, Finma, t=
o protect shareholders at the expense of AT1 holders.
The decision shook up the traditional hierarchy of bank creditors and under=
mined confidence in AT1s, which were introduced after the financial crisis =
as regulators tried to shift risk away from depositors and imposed greater =
capital requirements on banks in case of failure.
=E2=80=9CUBS are working frantically in the background to sort this out,=E2=
=80=9D said a bond fund manager who recently met the bank=E2=80=99s represe=
ntatives. =E2=80=9CThey need to give investors confidence that the capital =
structure won=E2=80=99t be inverted and the rules won=E2=80=99t be changed =
at the eleventh hour again.=E2=80=9D

UBS has to =E2=80=9Creplace up to $17bn of Credit Suisse AT1 bonds,=E2=80=
=9D not in the sense that it needs to raise new money to pay them off =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0those bonds are gone, it never has to pay them =E2=80=94=C2=A0b=
ut in the sense that they were cheap capital and it misses them. It wants t=
o sell $17 billion of AT1 securities to =E2=80=9Cfree up funds for sharehol=
der returns.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0In effect, it is going out to investors and sayi=
ng=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwouldn=E2=80=99t you like to charge us less for AT1 securi=
ties than you do for common stock?=E2=80=9D And the investors are saying =
=E2=80=9Cwell, but, like, 20 minutes ago, we found out that your=C2=A0AT1=
=C2=A0securities are actually junior to common stock, so shouldn=E2=80=99t =
we charge you more for them?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
There are two plausible answers to this. One is to tweak the terms to make =
the AT1s at least equal to common stock in a crisis:

One option under consideration is replacing UBS=E2=80=99s AT1 bonds, which =
are designed to be written down in the event the bank runs into trouble, wi=
th versions of the security that would be converted into equity, according =
to two people involved in the investor discussions.
=E2=80=9CEquity conversion is probably better and there is more demand if y=
ou do it like that,=E2=80=9D said another bond investor. =E2=80=9CBut we ar=
e not naive and don=E2=80=99t think it changes the risk.=E2=80=9D

The other answer is to just shrug and wait and figure that memories in this=
 market are very short and eventually everyone will forget what they were m=
ad about and buy the AT1s anyway.

