A general theory of art might be that artists create cultural cachet, and a=
rt collectors have cash, and the collectors trade their cash for the artist=
s=E2=80=99 cachet. For centuries the main form of cultural=C2=A0cachet that=
 artists could create was pretty pictures that looked nice hanging in colle=
ctors=E2=80=99 dining rooms and impressed their dinner guests, and so the p=
rettier the pictures were the more they were worth.
But eventually it got fairly easy=C2=A0to get pictures of arbitrary prettin=
ess, so pretty pictures do not carry the cachet and distinction that they o=
nce did, so collectors are not willing to pay that much for them. Collector=
s want more abstract and complicated forms of cultural cachet. They want th=
eir art to convey=C2=A0sophistication, and one very popular way to convey s=
ophistication is by showing that you are in some sense=C2=A0in on the joke.=
 If you bought Duchamp=E2=80=99s urinal, that showed that you were with it.
  [9]
=C2=A0If you gave gold to Yves Klein in exchange for  a receipt that you th=
en burned, you got nothing at all tangible, but you got cultural cachet. Yo=
u gave Klein money, and he did a prank on you, and then you laughed about i=
t=C2=A0together, which proved that you were cool in a way that hanging an O=
ld Master in your dining room could not. You got exactly what you paid for.=
 And Klein got the money.
  [10]

And then  non-fungible tokens were  invented to sort of  mass-produce this =
effect for the internet age.=C2=A0This should not work:=C2=A0Pretty picture=
s lost their edge in the art world because they became too easy to mass-pro=
duce, and now being-in-on-a-dumb-stunt has also become easy to mass-produce=
, and it too has, I think, lost its edge. For like seven minutes in 2021, y=
ou could say =E2=80=9Cgive me money and I will give you a receipt for nothi=
ng" and people would be like =E2=80=9Coh that=E2=80=99s a cool joke, here=
=E2=80=99s the money=E2=80=9D and feel good and sophisticated, but that was=
 very easy to do, so everyone did, so that market was saturated and it is, =
I insist, no longer cool.
But art museums maintain a record of the history of art, and the recent his=
tory of art involves a lot of pranks. A replica of Duchamp=E2=80=99s urinal=
 is  at the Tate. So now if you go to an art museum there will be some pret=
ty pictures but also some stunts, and the point of the stunts is for you to=
 look at them and say =E2=80=9Cha, I can=E2=80=99t believe the artist did t=
hat stunt, how cool,=E2=80=9D or at least, like, =E2=80=9Chmm, how interest=
ing, apparently people used to think these stunts were cool.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=
The stunts are often more noteworthy than the paintings. The San Francisco =
Museum of Modern Art seems to be prouder of  Erased de Kooning Drawing=C2=
=A0than it is of its  de Kooning drawings.=C2=A0
We talked a few years ago about an artist named Jens Haaning, who was commi=
ssioned by=C2=A0Kunsten, a Danish museum, to make a frankly pretty boring-s=
ounding artwork in which he would, like, put a bunch of cash in some glass =
frames to make a point about society or whatever. He borrowed the cash from=
 the museum, to put into the frames. And then he delivered the frames empty=
 and kept the cash. =E2=80=9CThe work of art is that I took their money,=E2=
=80=9D he said, really the most general possible work of art.=C2=A0
Nonetheless=C2=A0they sued him and yesterday=C2=A0they won, sort of:

A Danish artist who pocketed the cash he received from a museum to incorpor=
