  [1] Very casual numbers here. At noon today, the S&P 500 was at about 4,4=
25, and Bloomberg showed the Sept. 20, 2024, 4,425-strike put (SPX US 09/20=
/24 P4425 Equity) at about 211, or about 4.8% of notional.


  [2] That=E2=80=99s also true if it goes down by, like, 5.1%, due to the t=
ime value of money. Better to lose 5.1% over a year than to pay 5% at the b=
eginning of the year.


  [3] More complicated ways would be, like, identifying particular things t=
hat would be bad for your portfolio, and betting directly on those rather t=
han on the S&P. Also, like, you could buy a put spread where you take the f=
irst 5% of the loss and then get insured against the next 10% and then you =
take the rest, etc.; there's a whole industry devoted to selling optically =
cheap downside protection.


  [4] Or 1/250th, given that there are  250ish trading days in a year.


  [5] I don=E2=80=99t think that the actual mechanisms of bankruptcy clawba=
cks are that interesting here, but a lot of the stuff here consists of (1) =
Bankman-Fried taking money out of FTX and (2) him then giving the money to =
his parents. So the question is whether the parents, as subsequent transfer=
ees, are liable to the company to give it back. =E2=80=9CBankman-Fried acte=
d as a mere conduit, or, in the alternative, Bankman and Fried were subsequ=
ent transferees after the initial transfer of funds from Alameda Ltd. to Ba=
nkman-Fried, and Bankman and Fried lacked good faith with respect to such t=
ransfers,=E2=80=9D is the sort of argument the complaint makes.


  [6] =E2=80=9CFacing Up to Risk=E2=80=9D didn=E2=80=99t make the cut, or =
=E2=80=9CEx Ante/Ex Post,=E2=80=9D but I suppose if you were litigating thi=
s case for the bankruptcy estate you might want to skim those to see if you=
 can mine them for irony.


  [7] He also, unlike Fried, became an actual employee of FTX, which led to=
 this awkward exchange:  =E2=80=9COn January 12, 2022, despite Bankman=E2=
=80=99s employment agreement with FTX US detailing a $200,000 annual salary=
, Bankman complained to FTX US Head of Administration that he was receiving=
 gross pay of only $16,667 per month from FTX US, when he was =E2=80=98supp=
osed to be getting $1M/yr, starting in December. So that would be a bit mor=
e than $80,000 a month, gross=E2=80=A6=E2=80=99 Bankman promptly brought hi=
s discontent to Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s attention, emailing his son, =E2=80=
=98Gee, Sam I don=E2=80=99t know what to say here. This is the first [I] ha=
ve heard of the 200K a year salary! Putting Barbara on this.=E2=80=99 In ot=
her words, Bankman lobbied his son to massively increase his own salary.=E2=
=80=9D And cc=E2=80=99ed Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s mom!


  [8] I mean, if you asked the US Securities and Exchange Commission, they=
=E2=80=99d probably tell you it was selling unregistered securities: It was=
 selling crypto tokens that the SEC has argued elsewhere are securities. Bu=
t the SEC didn=E2=80=99t bother charging FTX with this because, you know, b=
igger fish to fry.


  [9] In fact Duchamp  does not seem to have sold his original urinal =E2=
