<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">0DTE</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s say you own a bunch of stocks, s=
ay $1 million worth of the stocks in the S&amp;P 500 Index. You think they =
will go up (that=E2=80=99s why you own them), but you worry that they might=
 go down. You can buy insurance against that risk: You can pay someone a fe=
e now, and she will guarantee you that, in a year, your S&amp;P 500 stocks =
will be worth at least $1 million. If they=E2=80=99re not, she=E2=80=99ll p=
ay you the difference. (If they=E2=80=99re worth more than $1 million, you =
keep the gains, but she keeps the fee.) This is a put option.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The fee for that insurance is about $50,000: Y=
ou pay about 5% of the value of your portfolio to insure it against a drop =
for one year.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background=
-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0That=E2=80=99s kind of a lot? If the S&amp;P goes down by 20%, yo=
u=E2=80=99ll be happy you bought insurance, but if it goes down by 4% you w=
on=E2=80=99t be: You=E2=80=99d have been better off taking that loss and no=
t paying 5% upfront.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> If the S&amp;P goes=C2=A0<em>up=C2=A0</em>by 20%, you won=E2=80=99t mi=
nd your insurance that much =E2=80=94=C2=A0you still made 15%, net of insur=
ance costs =E2=80=94=C2=A0but if it goes up by 5% you=E2=80=99ll be bummed;=
 the cost of insurance wiped out all of your gains.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You might want cheaper insurance. One way to g=
et cheaper insurance is to insure against only particular risks. One relati=
vely simple way to do that=C2=A0would be to buy insurance only on particula=
r=C2=A0<em>days</em>.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> If the Federal Reserve has a monetary=C2=A0policy announcement schedul=
ed one Wednesday afternoon, and you worry that the Fed might raise rates an=
d that this will be bad for your stocks, you could buy insurance on your st=
ocks for=C2=A0<em>that day:=C2=A0</em>If your stocks go down that day, you =
get paid the difference, but if they don=E2=80=99t, your insurance premium =
is wasted. That insurance is relatively cheap: Buying a day of protection c=
osts a lot less than buying a year of protection. I mean, it costs a lot mo=
re=C2=A0<em>per day=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0a one-day put costs more than =
1/365th as much<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgrou=
nd-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> as a one-year put =E2=80=94 but if you pick the right days maybe you s=
ave money.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32765671.258423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDktMTkvYS1wb3B1bGFyLW9wdGlvbnMtdHJhZGUtZ2l=
2ZXMtaW52ZXN0b3JzLWEtMS0wMDAtc3RvY2stYmV0LWZvci1qdXN0LTE_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkxOT=
IzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX=
3Rlcm09MjMwOTE5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf0=
025d0a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">  Lu Wang reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors are wagering on the daily gyrations =
of American equity benchmarks by dashing in and out of trading contracts th=
at expire within 24 hours =E2=80=94 known by the =E2=80=9C0DTE=E2=80=9D mon=
iker =E2=80=94 with less upfront capital than meets the eye. The hidden fue=
l for the frenzy: Quirks in the ecosystem of the derivatives marketplace th=
at makes these zero-days-to-expiry options look cheap.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The best way to observe the phenomenon is in t=
he difference between how much investors are actually spending on 0DTE and =
the notional value of those options =E2=80=94 that is, how much exposure th=
ey are getting to the underlying asset via the contracts.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the latter, the notional trading volume of =
0DTE for the S&amp;P 500 currently averages a beefy $516 billion a day, acc=
ording to data compiled by Cboe Global Markets. Yet the actual amount of mo=
ney paid out for them, or the premium, is only $520 million.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Put another way, traders are getting $1,000 of=
 stock exposure for every dollar they spend on 0DTE. They would need to spe=
nd 10 times that to get the same equity position using derivatives with a l=
onger lifespan, a Bloomberg analysis on Cboe=E2=80=99s data shows.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThey are the fantasy football of opti=
on trading,=E2=80=9D said Dennis Davitt, co-manager of the MDP Low Volatili=
ty Fund. =E2=80=9CYou spend a dollar and you see if it goes your way. Then =
you=E2=80=99re done at the end of the day.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Getting exposure to $1,000 worth of stocks for=
ever costs about $1,000. Getting exposure to $1,000 worth of stocks for=C2=
=A0<em>one day=C2=A0</em>costs about $1. What is the economic case for gett=
ing exposure to $1,000 worth of stocks for one day? Why would you want that=
? Oh, mostly gambling, but also very targeted hedging:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On March 22, for example, when the Federal Res=
erve was about to announce its monetary policy in the afternoon, the S&amp;=
P 500 opened at about 4,002. At that time, an at-the-money put =E2=80=94 a =
protective contract where the strike price is essentially the same as where=
 the index is actually trading =E2=80=94 cost about $26 for an expiry in th=
e same session. A similar contract maturing two days later could be bought =
for roughly $37 =E2=80=94 or 42% more than the 0DTE.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThere are very meticulous use cases f=
or 0DTE options that did not exist previously,=E2=80=9D said=C2=A0Jonathan =
Zaionz, senior derivatives analyst at Cboe. =E2=80=9CSince people are takin=
g shorter term views and/or hedging with 0DTE, they don=E2=80=99t need to p=
ay as much in time premium compared to longer term strategies.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I want to read a story about a long-term buy-a=
nd-hold passive index investor who (1) buys a bunch of the S&amp;P 500, (2)=
 never sells it and (3) has reeeeeeally good timing doing occasional hedges=
 with 0DTE options. I am not sure that that=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>much=C2=A0</=
em>of what is going on here, and I=E2=80=99m not sure that that would exact=
ly count as =E2=80=9Clong-term buy-and-hold passive index investing,=E2=80=
=9D but it would be cool.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, last week <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/32765671.258423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNv=
bS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDktMTQvemVyby1kYXktb3B0aW9ucy1ib29tLWlzLXNwaWx=
saW5nLWludG8tNy00LXRyaWxsaW9uLWV0Zi1tYXJrZXQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkxOTIzX01PTkVZU1=
RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwO=
TE5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB309b4340" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">  Wang and Isabelle Lee reported</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Defiance ETFs is launching a fund on Thursday =
that sells ultra short-dated options on the Nasdaq 100 as part of its strat=
egy. The product will be the first in the market to utilize so-called zero-=
day-to-expiration contracts, or 0DTE, as part of its design.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The fund will write puts =E2=80=94 bearish con=
tracts that offer the buyer protection from index declines =E2=80=94 to gen=
erate income. By offering options with such a short lifespan, the Defiance =
Nasdaq 100 Enhanced Options Income ETF (ticker QQQY) will be able to sell c=
ontracts more frequently, according to the issuer.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/32765671.258423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZGVmaWFuY2VldGZzLmNvbS93=
cC1jb250ZW50L3VwbG9hZHMvZnVuZGRvY3MvcXFxeS9RUVFZLVByb3NwZWN0dXMucGRmP2hzQ3R=
hVHJhY2tpbmc9ZmU4NDAxODMtN2E2MC00NzE0LTkyOGMtNDQ1ZjRmMzhhNzBhJTdDNzYyMzg4NG=
MtYWMwYS00YzMwLWI3NzAtMjdlMDI5NjI4ZmE1/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc0954478" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> the prospectus</a>. Basically the ETF sells at-the-money=C2=A0or sl=
ightly out-of-the-money puts each day; if the S&amp;P goes up it pockets th=
e premium, and even if it=E2=80=99s down or flat it collects=C2=A0the (smal=
l) time value of the options. The natural way to think about this ETF is =
=E2=80=9Ca lot of people are really excited about buying 0DTE options, so t=
hey are probably overpaying, and probably a lot of them are doing it for du=
mb gambling reasons, so we should be on the other side of that.=E2=80=9D</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The downside is of course that if everyone is =
buying lottery tickets, they might be dumb, and being on the other side mig=
ht be a positive-expected-value trade, but <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/32765671.258423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucmV1dGVycy5jb20vYn=
VzaW5lc3MvZmluYW5jZS9uZXctZXRmLWxvb2tzLXRhcC1ob3QtbWFya2V0LXplcm8tZGF5LW9wd=
GlvbnMtMjAyMy0wOS0xNC8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB41167062" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> selling =
lottery tickets is risky</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">"QQQY is attempting to timely scratch two itch=
es, potential income from an asset that doesn=E2=80=99t typically generate =
income and exposure to the sudden popularity of trading ODTE options," said=
 Lois Gregson, senior ETF analyst at FactSet Research Systems. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">"The strategy is similar to picking up dimes i=
n front of a bulldozer. The income potential is there, but there are times =
you could also get run over," Gregson said.</p>
</blockquote>
