<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bank additional tier 1 capital securities are,=
 I think, basically a trick. The trick works like this:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">AT1s kind of look like bonds =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0they pay regular interest, they usually get paid back after five o=
r 10 years =E2=80=94=C2=A0so investors treat them like bonds. In particular=
, the interest payment on a bank=E2=80=99s AT1s will normally be lower than=
 the bank=E2=80=99s cost of equity capital, and so banks will issue AT1s be=
cause they=E2=80=99re cheaper than issuing equity.</li>=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">If the bank runs into trouble, the AT1s act like stock: Th=
ey absorb losses so that governments, taxpayers, depositors, etc. don=E2=80=
=99t have to. The AT1s are sort of the first line of defense against bank b=
ailouts. In some ways, some AT1s are actually=C2=A0<em>junior to=C2=A0equit=
y:=C2=A0</em>Many AT1s, by their terms, go to zero if a bank=E2=80=99s comm=
on equity capital ratio falls below 7%; at that point, the common stock is =
still worth something but the AT1s are worth nothing. This fact makes regul=
ators like AT1s =E2=80=94=C2=A0they are very helpfully loss-absorbing =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0and so regulators treat them as good bank capital, a good subst=
itute for=C2=A0some of a bank=E2=80=99s common stock.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors think of AT1s as almost like bonds; =
regulators think of AT1s as almost like stock. And so banks can issue AT1s =
that, for regulatory purposes, are treated almost like stock, but that, eco=
nomically, are not nearly as expensive as stock. So banks often optimize th=
eir capital structures by issuing as much AT1 capital as they are allowed t=
o. A big European bank with a lot of common equity but no AT1 capital is le=
aving money on the table: It should buy back some stock and issue more AT1s=
 to be more efficient.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A few years ago <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/32765671.258423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNv=
bS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDItMTMvc2FudGFuZGVyLWRpZG4tdC1wYXktaXRzLW5=
vbi1kZWJ0P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MTkyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3=
NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDkxOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZ=
g/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcdf2c709" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">I wrote</a>: =E2=80=9CIf the r=
egulators think that they=E2=80=99re equity and the investors think that th=
ey=E2=80=99re debt, probably someone is wrong!=E2=80=9D And then we have ch=
ecked in a few times when the investors have been wrong. (I should say, I t=
end not to write about AT1s when they just pay regular interest and then ge=
t redeemed at par at their first call date; <em>most </em>of the time, the =
investors are right that AT1s look like bonds.) Most notably, when Credit S=
uisse Group AG blew up and was acquired by UBS Group AG this year, some $17=
 billion of Credit Suisse AT1s were written down to zero, and the holders w=
ere understandably upset. In particular, they were upset that Credit Suisse=
=E2=80=99s common=C2=A0shareholders=C2=A0got paid something, while the AT1s=
 got zeroed. If you think that AT1s are bonds, then this is an outrage: The=
 bonds are supposed to be senior to the common stock. If you think that AT1=
s are the first loss absorber to prevent bailouts, as Swiss regulators do, =
then this is great. (As I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/32765671.258423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGl=
jbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjAvdWJzLWdvdC1jcmVkaXQtc3Vpc3NlLWZvci1hbG1vc3Qtbm90aGluZz=
9jbXBpZD1CQkQwOTE5MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9b=
mV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA5MTkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB2c090246" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">argued at the time</a>, the Credit Suiss=
e AT1s were=C2=A0<em>designed by their terms to go to zero even if the stoc=
k is worth something</em>, so the regulators are right as a general matter,=
 though the AT1 holders have some decent technical arguments about the exac=
t events that triggered their writedown.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From UBS=E2=80=99s perspective, this was basic=
ally a sweet deal: It was able to buy Credit Suisse and get rid of $17 bill=
ion of Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s debt, or quasi-debt, because the Swiss regul=
ators insisted that Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s AT1s vanish. On the other hand,=
 it leaves UBS with an inefficient capital structure: That $17 billion of A=
T1s was cheap capital, and now it is gone; zeroing it effectively increased=
 UBS=E2=80=99s common equity capital, but <em>common equity is not what it =
wants.=C2=A0</em>Efficiency demands that UBS issue more AT1s to buy back so=
me stock. Because,=C2=A0<em>still</em>, AT1 is cheaper than common equity,=
=C2=A0<em>even for UBS</em>, even after the recent high-profile Credit Suis=
se experience of zeroing the AT1s while the common equity got paid.=C2=A0</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, probably the AT1 is cheaper. Yesterday t=
he Financial Times <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/32765671.258423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvYzM1NmFjMDctODZiYS00Yz=
BiLWI3M2ItMjRmZDViN2IzM2Fm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB504553c8" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">check=
ed in with UBS on its AT1 program</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">UBS is under pressure to replace up to $17bn o=
f Credit Suisse AT1 bonds in the coming years to improve the efficiency of =
the enlarged bank=E2=80=99s capital structure and free up funds for shareho=
lder returns and potential acquisitions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But some investors remain wary after bondholde=
rs lost billions of dollars during the rescue of Credit Suisse when an emer=
gency law brought in by the Swiss government allowed the country=E2=80=99s =
financial regulator, Finma, to protect shareholders at the expense of AT1 h=
olders.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The decision shook up the traditional hierarch=
y of bank creditors and undermined confidence in AT1s, which were introduce=
d after the financial crisis as regulators tried to shift risk away from de=
positors and imposed greater capital requirements on banks in case of failu=
re.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CUBS are working frantically in the ba=
ckground to sort this out,=E2=80=9D said a bond fund manager who recently m=
et the bank=E2=80=99s representatives. =E2=80=9CThey need to give investors=
 confidence that the capital structure won=E2=80=99t be inverted and the ru=
les won=E2=80=99t be changed at the eleventh hour again.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">UBS has to =E2=80=9Creplace up to $17bn of Cre=
dit Suisse AT1 bonds,=E2=80=9D not in the sense that it needs to raise new =
money to pay them off =E2=80=94=C2=A0those bonds are gone, it never has to =
pay them =E2=80=94=C2=A0but in the sense that they were cheap capital and i=
t misses them. It wants to sell $17 billion of AT1 securities to =E2=80=9Cf=
ree up funds for shareholder returns.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0In effect, it is going =
out to investors and saying=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwouldn=E2=80=99t you like to char=
ge us less for AT1 securities than you do for common stock?=E2=80=9D And th=
e investors are saying =E2=80=9Cwell, but, like, 20 minutes ago, we found o=
ut that your=C2=A0AT1=C2=A0securities are actually junior to common stock, =
so shouldn=E2=80=99t we charge you <em>more </em>for them?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are two plausible answers to this. One i=
s to tweak the terms to make the AT1s at least equal to common stock in a c=
risis:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One option under consideration is replacing UB=
S=E2=80=99s AT1 bonds, which are designed to be written down in the event t=
he bank runs into trouble, with versions of the security that would be conv=
erted into equity, according to two people involved in the investor discuss=
ions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CEquity conversion is probably better =
and there is more demand if you do it like that,=E2=80=9D said another bond=
 investor. =E2=80=9CBut we are not naive and don=E2=80=99t think it changes=
 the risk.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other answer is to just shrug and wait and=
 figure that memories in this market are very short and eventually everyone=
 will forget what they were mad about and buy the AT1s anyway.</p>
